Viewport

Viewport is a window into the game world

A Viewport renders the world, either in 2D or 3D.

All Godot games come with a “root” viewport to render the world, which is only visible at runtime.

Adding a Viewport node to a scene creates another window to the game world and renders it to a texture.

In Godot 3, you use viewports not only for split-screen but also for render targets: anytime you need to render to a texture.

In this guide, you will learn how to:

  • Set up a Viewport.
  • Create split screen multiplayer.
  • Take screenshots in your game.
  • Place floating nametags on 3D characters.
  • Put a 3D character in a 2D world.
  • Make 3D portals.

Setting up a Viewport

Before we use a Viewport, let’s look at how to set one up. Every Viewport needs:

  1. Child nodes to render.
  2. A camera to view its content, at least in 3D.
  3. A size to control the render resolution. The higher the value, the more rendering performance the viewport requires.

The Viewport itself doesn’t display anything. It only renders its content.

To display a viewport’s content, you can use either a ViewportContainer node or a ViewportTexture resource which you attach to a TextureRect.

Using a ViewportContainer is the fastest way to display a Viewport on the screen: all you need is to add the Viewport as a child of a ViewportContainer.

We cover how to use a ViewportTexture instead later in Rendering the Viewport onto an in-game object.

Make sure the Viewport node itself has the Size property set in the Inspector. You can also enable Stretch on its ViewportContainer to let the container control the viewport’s resolution dynamically.

Lastly, when adding a Camera to your viewport, be sure to set it to Current in the Inspector.

In 3D, you need at least one Camera set to Current to view the world. In 2D, a viewport without a camera works and uses the bounds displayed in the 2D main screen.

If a Viewport stops rendering in-editor, in-game, or if other issues crop up, check out the Troubleshooting part of this guide.

Viewport’s key features

Now that we have a Viewport set up in a scene, we can look at some key features.

Adjusting the viewport size

The Size property controls the viewport’s base render resolution.

If you’re using a ViewportContainer, you can adjust the size of its child viewport by enabling Stretch. Then, resize the container in the 2D editor to take control of the child viewport’s Size.

On top of that, ViewportContainer offers the Stretch Shrink property, which divides the displayed viewport’s resolution. This helps to implement rendering performance settings in your game.

Using transparency

You can hide the viewport’s background to only render the nodes that the camera sees, without the background. This is really handy for showing a 3D model over a 2D scene, or making a 2D minimap transparent over the game view.

To make your viewport’s background transparent, enable Transparent Bg in the Inspector.

Choosing to use sampling and effects

If you’re showing 2D pixel art, you may want to disable sampling to boost performance, and to prevent the viewport from smoothing your pixels.

To do so, set Rendering -> Usage to 2D No Sampling.

For 3D, if you’re not going to use post-processing effects or shaders on a viewport, you can set 3D No Effects to boost performance.

Rendering the Viewport onto an in-game object

For every node with a Texture property in Godot, the Inspector gives the option to add a ViewportTexture.

This is also known as a render target: displaying a viewport as a texture. You can use that with Sprite nodes, in 3D materials, and anywhere you can display a texture.

To use a ViewportTexture:

  1. Add a Viewport to a scene.
  2. On a Sprite node or another node with a Texture property, assign a new ViewportTexture to the slot.
  3. A window appears. There, select your Viewport node from the scene tree and save the scene.

Note: Several errors can come up after saving at this point. While most aren’t game-breaking, you can fix them by going to the Troubleshooting section.

How to use a Viewport in practice

Now let’s take a look at how a Viewport node can be used in Godot.

Split screen multiplayer

To display a split screen, you can use two ViewportContainer nodes, each with a child Viewport.

Both viewports should have a camera that looks into either the 2D or 3D world.

In this example, we used a GridContainer node to automatically place and resize the containers.

You generally want to turn on Stretch on ViewportContainer nodes. That way, they’ll resize their viewport to match the displayed area.

To have the GridContainer take the entire screen, we placed it inside a CanvasLayer and applied Layout -> Full Rect to it.

To make sure the ViewportContainer fills up the grid too, set its horizontal and vertical Size Flags to Expand.

You only need the CanvasLayer node if, like us, your scene has a Spatial node as its root, as this prevents us from changing UI nodes’ layout.

You can read more about CanvasLayer nodes in the CanvasLayer guide.

With the split screen set up, you can duplicate the ViewportContainer with Ctrl+D and watch more windows enter the screen. You can adjust the distribution of containers using the Columns property on the GridContainer.

To move each player individually, you’ll need to assign them different controls. We cover the basics in our Local multiplayer input tutorial.

Taking screenshots

Screenshots are a common feature for games with social or randomly-generated content.

You can capture them using a Viewport, by saving their rendered image data to a file.

In this demo, we use a CanvasLayer with a Label and an AnimationPlayer as children. We use them to fade the label after successfully saving a screenshot image.

To save screenshots, we have a script that’ll access the root viewport, one created automatically by Godot at the root of our game’s scene tree.

This script generates screenshot names and gets images from the viewport.

# This is the template for our screenshot filenames:
#
# - %s is a placeholder to print variables as-is.
# - %02d takes a number and ensure adds leading a leading zero as necessary to
#   ensure there are always 2 digits.
#
# Example output filename: "Node_Essentials_2021-06-19_10-40-00.png"
const FILENAME_TEMPLATE := "%s_%s-%02d-%02d_%02d-%02d-%02d"

# Our Godot project's name, which we store to add in screenshot file names.
onready var game_name: String = ProjectSettings.get_setting("application/config/name")

onready var _anim_player := $CanvasLayer/AnimationPlayer
onready var _label := $CanvasLayer/Label

You can change your game’s name in Project > Project Settings > Application > Config > Name.

Now for the main event, the screenshot function. The essentials of this function are:

  • Call get_texture().get_data() on the Viewport to return it as an upside-down image.
  • Flip the image with flip_y() so it’s rightside-up.
  • Call save_png("user://filename.png") to save it to the user folder.

Instead of saving the screenshot as filename.png, we can get the date and time from the OS to create a timestamped screenshot.

You can see some string formatting in action with the following screenshot code:

## Generates an image name, gets the Viewport data, and saves it as a png file in
## the user folder.
func take_screenshot() -> void:
    var date: Dictionary = OS.get_datetime()
    var image_name = (
        FILENAME_TEMPLATE % [
            game_name,
            date["year"],
            date["month"],
            date["day"],
            date["hour"],
            date["minute"],
            date["second"]
        ]
    )
    # We get the root viewport's texture data to save it as an image file. The
    # function returns the rendered pixels.
    var image: Image = get_viewport().get_texture().get_data()
    # In OpenGL images render mirrored vertically.
    #
    # Godot automatically flips images when displaying them on your screen, but
    # here, we need to do it manually.
    image.flip_y()
    # And finally, we save the screenshot to the user's directory using the
    # image's save_png() method.
    image.save_png("user://%s.png" % [image_name])
    # We display a label to notify the player we saved a screenshot.
    _label.text = "Screenshot taken: \"%s\"" % [image_name]
    _anim_player.stop(true)
    _anim_player.play("fade")

We use string formatting to integrate the date and time into the filename as a single string. The % [] at the end goes through every percent sign, and replaces them with the variables in the brackets

You can learn more about Godot string formatting by reading GDScript Format Strings on the Godot docs.

Lastly, we need to bind one key to take screenshots, and another key to open the screenshot folder:

func _unhandled_input(event: InputEvent) -> void:
    # We set this action to F9 in our project.
    if event.is_action_pressed("take_screenshot"):
        take_screenshot()
    # And we mapped this action to F10.
    if event.is_action("open_user_directory"):
        open_user_directory()

Here is the function to open the directory in which we save screenshots.

## Opens the user:// folder. This code works on all supported platforms.
func open_user_directory() -> void:
    OS.shell_open(OS.get_user_data_dir())

You should now be able to take screenshots without UI in the way.

In this example, we used the user:// directory to save screenshots. You can learn more about it in the official manual

Placing Labels in 3D

In MMOs, nametags are essential to know who you’re playing with.

You can add labels in 3D by rendering them to a texture, then displaying this texture on a QuadMesh in the 3D world.

To do so, you need a Viewport, a Label, and a MeshInstance.

The Viewport renders the Label and we display its output via a material assigned to the MeshInstance’s Mesh via a ViewportTexture.

When using viewports as render targets, the scene tree order matters. The mesh’s texture has to pull from the viewport after rendering, so the mesh should be below the viewport node in the scene tree.

Then, Viewport nodes render images flipped vertically by default.

As a result, the Viewport node should have Render Target -> V Flip enabled, otherwise the ViewportTexture will appear upside-down.

You should also enable Transparent Bg to render the label over a transparent background.

Then, we want to assign a QuadMesh to the MeshInstance’s Mesh property. This is essentially a flat surface like PlaneMesh, although we can make it always face the camera.

Sizing the viewport and mesh

The viewport and mesh both have a Size property. To prevent the label from looking squished, they need to use the same aspect ratio.

We’re using a ratio of 3:1 by setting the viewport size to Vector2(300, 100) and mesh size to Vector2(3, 1).

The MeshInstance’s Mesh should have a SpatialMaterial with the Flags -> Transparent and Flags -> Unshaded turned on to render the text without the scene’s lights affecting it.

You also want to assign a ViewportTexture as its Albedo -> Texture. Set it to target your label’s viewport and you should be able to see the text in your 3D scene.

To make the text always face the camera, set the material’s Parameters -> Billboard Mode to Particle Billboard.

Note: If you get the error Can't create a ViewportTexture on this resource because it's not set as local to scene, check that both the QuadMesh resource and its SpatialMaterial have their Resource -> Local To Scene property turned on.

If you want your nametags to fade out over distance, set Distance Fade -> Mode -> Pixel Alpha.

You can use Max Distance and Min Distance to control the distance. Making Max Distance smaller than Min Distance will fade the nametag out as you get further away.

The nametag should be floating around in 3D space now! Objects in front of the nametag will hide it.

You can also add code to change the Label at runtime. For example, you can connect a LineEdit node’s text_changed signal to match the Label’s text:

func _on_LineEdit_text_changed(new_text: String) -> void:
    _nametag_label.text = new_text

Note: if any viewport-related errors have come up in the console, go to the Troubleshooting section of this guide.

Note: You can use Sprite3D for nametags instead of a MeshInstance.

Sprite3D has the upside of scaling itself using Pixel Size. MeshInstance has the upside of letting you use shapes other than squares. In either case, you’ll need to use a ViewportTexture.

3D character in 2D world

Some games use 3D models over a 2D world. For example, Oxenfree uses painted 2D backgrounds, but displays its characters in 3D.

Game: Oxenfree (2016)

A Viewport and Sprite can be added to a 2D character controller. The Viewport should have a Camera, and 3D skin as children:

The camera points at the AstronautSkin node to show it on the Viewport. Then, the Sprite is given a ViewportTexture that points at the Viewport, showing the 3D scene in 2D.

Make sure the Viewport has Transparent Bg and Render Target -> V Flip enabled. You should be able to see your 3D scene through the Sprite.

If there’s any issues, check the Troubleshooting section of this guide.

Now that we can see the 3D scene in 2D, the character controller’s CollisionShape2D can be fit to what’s visible from the Viewport.

You can learn more about creating a character controller in the guide for KinematicBody2D.

Changing graphics settings

Because Viewport renders the game world to the screen, it also can adjust some graphics settings. This is useful for 3D games where the user’s device will vary.

In our demo, we created a Viewport node in the scene to help you better understand what’s happening in Godot.

You can apply the same settings on the game’s root viewport. To get the root viewport node, call get_viewport() from your code.

There are four main ways a Viewport can adjust graphics settings:

  • Size (Resolution)
  • MSAA (Multisample Anti-Aliasing)
  • FXAA (Fast Approximate Anti-Aliasing)
  • Shadow atlas size

To let the user change all of these settings, we’ll add different types for the user to adjust.

OptionButton is useful when we want to show the user a detailed list, like screen resolutions and MSAA settings.

HSlider adjusts a single value, we use this to give a general “low, medium, high, max” option for shadow quality.

CheckBox is good for boolean settings like FXAA.

We put these Control nodes in VBoxContainer and HBoxContainer nodes so Godot could line them up automatically. Using containers like this is optional, and only the two OptionButton nodes, the HSlider, and the CheckBox are necessary:

In a script on the root, we can save some setup time by connecting the Control nodes to functions we’ll create in the future.

export var target_viewport := NodePath()

onready var _viewport: Viewport = get_node(target_viewport)

onready var _resolution: OptionButton = $VBoxContainer/Resolution/OptionButton
onready var _shadow_quality: Slider = $VBoxContainer/ShadowQuality/Slider
onready var _MSAA: OptionButton = $VBoxContainer/MSAA/OptionButton
onready var _FXAA: CheckBox = $VBoxContainer/FXAA/CheckBox


func _ready():
    _populate_resolutions()
    
    _resolution.connect("item_selected", self, "set_resolution")
    _shadow_quality.connect("value_changed", self, "set_shadow_quality")
    _MSAA.connect("item_selected", self, "set_msaa")
    _FXAA.connect("toggled", self, "set_fxaa")

The _populate_resolutions() function needs to be made ahead of time since it’s called in _ready(). Keep _populate_resolutions() blank for now:

func _populate_resolutions -> void:
    pass

Before moving on, we need to choose which Viewport to adjust, and set the target_viewport variable in the Inspector. Point this to the Viewport node in the scene.

If you want to use the root Viewport, delete the target_viewport variable and assign _viewport to the root instead:

onready var _viewport: Viewport = get_tree().get_root()

The rest of the guide will go through what each property does, and how to adjust these properties with the Control nodes we laid out earlier.

Size (Resolution)

Godot does not change the user’s monitor resolution like other engines. In fullscreen, the root Viewport changes its size to match your game window. This is a problem in 3D, where some users with a high-resolution monitor (4k, 2k, etc.) can’t render 3D at their monitor’s native resolution.

The solution is to reduce the Viewport’s stretch transform. This is a coordinate system unique to viewports that let them reduce their rendered pixels, while keeping their size and position on-screen.

If the Viewport has Size Override Stretch enabled then the size property will instead change the stretch transform.

You can quickly change a viewport’s stretch transform through a ViewportContainer by:

  1. Enabling Stretch on ViewportContainer.
  2. Adjusting the Size on the Viewport.

Your viewport will remain in the same place on the screen, but its resolution will be different. The viewport’s stretch transform is changed, so the density of pixels over the screen changes. You can return the viewport to normal by unchecking Stretch.

If we want the user to adjust the Viewport stretch transform like this, we can give users a drop-down list of common resolutions like in other game engines.

The OptionButton node is great at drop-down options. We can use one that we first added in the setup. First, create a list of common resolutions to support in scene’s script:

const SUPPORTED_RESOLUTIONS := [
    Vector2(1920, 1080),
    Vector2(1366, 768),
    Vector2(1280, 720),
    Vector2(960, 540),
]

Then, you can fill in the empty _populate_resolutions() function to pass this list of resolutions to the OptionButton. This will give it selectable items based on the supported resolutions list:

## Fills the resolution drop-down menu with supported resolutions.
func _populate_resolutions() -> void:
    for index in SUPPORTED_RESOLUTIONS.size():
        var resolution: Vector2 = SUPPORTED_RESOLUTIONS[index]
        var resolution_as_string := "{x}x{y}".format({x = resolution.x, y = resolution.y})
        _resolution.add_item(resolution_as_string, index)

We need one more function to read the OptionButton’s selected index, and to set the Viewport’s size as needed.

From the _ready() function set up earlier, this function is already connected to the OptionButton’s item_selected signal.

func set_resolution(index: int) -> void:
    assert(
        index < SUPPORTED_RESOLUTIONS.size(),
        "Trying to set the viewport to an unsupported resolution."
    )
    _viewport.size = SUPPORTED_RESOLUTIONS[index]

You should be able to modify the resolution of your game on a Viewport node. You can look to other parts of this guide for other graphics options.

To adjust the stretch transform of the root Viewport, enable size_override_stretch in code, and use set_size_override() to set its size and position:

onready var _root := get_tree().get_root()

func _ready() -> void:
# enable using the stretch transform to adjust resolution
    _root.set_size_override_stretch(true)
# set window size to 1920 x 1080, set the Viewport's top-left corner to window's
# top-left corner
    _root.set_size_override(true, Vector2(1920, 1080), Vector2(0,0))
# set stretch transform to 400 pixels by 400 pixels
    _root.size = Vector2(400, 400)

You can adjust the first Vector2 of set_size_override() to change the game window size. The _root.size represents the stretch transform.

MSAA (Multisample Anti-Aliasing)

MSAA, or Multisample Anti-Aliasing, helps prevent jagged edges in games by fetching more data per pixel before drawing the screen’s contents.

The options for MSAA are 2x, 4x, 8x, and 16x. There are also equivalents of 2x and 4x intended for AndroidVR, which we will not use here.

OptionButton provides a dropdown list of items, and each item has an index. We can read the selected item’s index to set the viewport’s MSAA value.

func set_msaa(level: int) -> void:
    _viewport.msaa = level

If you did the setup earlier, this function will already be connected to the OptionButton’s item_selected signal.

Now that the script is setup, the OptionButton needs items added manually. Click on the 2D view, then click Items at the top of the editor view. Add five items and give the items these names:

  • Disabled
  • 2x
  • 4x
  • 8x
  • 16x

Your settings menu will now let you adjust MSAA on the Viewport.

FXAA (Fast Approximate Anti-Aliasing)

FXAA or Fast Approximate Anti-Aliasing is a quicker way to smooth out the edges of geometry than MSAA.

It takes the contents of the screen and blurs it. This is a cheap way to avoid sharp edges, but it can degrade visual detail.

From the earlier setup, the CheckBox in the _ready() script is already connected to the Viewport’s FXAA setting. Viewport has a function called set_fxaa() which is either true or false.

Look back to your _ready() script from setup, and notice this line that connects the pressed state of the CheckBox to the FXAA setting on the Viewport:

_FXAA.connect("toggled", self, "set_fxaa")

Shadow atlas size

Shadow atlas size is the amount of texture space given to the engine to render realtime shadows. The higher the atlas size, the sharper and more-accurate the shadows will be, at the cost of performance.

This guide will use an HSlider with four levels of shadow quality to adjust. It will adjust both the Viewport’s shadow atlas size, and the ProjectSettings for shadow filtering. Both shadow settings are adjusted to highlight what’s changeable from the user’s perspective.

Check that the HSlider has a Max Value of 3 and a Min Value of 0.

Back in the main script, we need to recreate the ProjectSettings enumerations for shadow filtering, so we know which filtering setting we’re using.

Disabled filtering means jagged, aliased shadows. PCF5 provides smooth shadows as a tradeoff between quality and performance. PCF13 shadows are even smoother, and run slower. We’ll map these to the HSlider’s four settings, leaving the first setting to disable shadows entirely.

enum ShadowFilter { DISABLED, PCF5, PCF13 }

# Maps slider values to ShadowFilter settings
const SHADOW_SLIDER = {
    0 : ShadowFilter.DISABLED,
    1 : ShadowFilter.DISABLED,
    2 : ShadowFilter.PCF5,
    3 : ShadowFilter.PCF13
}

A shadow atlas size of 1 will result in very splotchy shadows, instead of setting the slider value to the atlas size, we’ll use a default size of 1024 and go from there. This script also points to the ProjectSettings shadow filtering path.

const SHADOW_FILTER_SETTING := "rendering/quality/shadows/filter_mode"
const DEFAULT_SHADOW_ATLAS_SIZE := 1024

Now we can create the function that will change our shadow filtering and shadow atlas size when the HSlider is adjusted:

func set_shadow_quality(value: int):
    assert(
        value < SHADOW_SLIDER.size(),
        "Trying to set shadow filtering to an unmappped value."
    )
    # enable space for the shadows, otherwise don't give them space to render
    _viewport.shadow_atlas_size = DEFAULT_SHADOW_ATLAS_SIZE if value != 0 else 0
    # The Project-wide shadow filtering is the main visual change in this slider
    ProjectSettings.set(SHADOW_FILTER_SETTING, SHADOW_SLIDER[value])

This script uses a ternary to check if the HSlider is zero. If it is, the shadow atlas size becomes zero, and shadows are disabled for the Viewport. Otherwise, they’re set to the default.

You can read more about the many different settings for shadows in the Godot docs tutorial on lights and shadows.

Reset to default settings

Some users can get lost in understanding what certain graphics settings do, and may accidentally enable or disable a setting that drastically changes performance or visual quality.

This step shows setting up one default, but you can always add more buttons for preset “high,” “medium,” and “low” settings.

With all of our setter functions and Control node connections, we can set the sliders back to their defaults. The HSlider and CheckBox nodes will automatically emit appropriate signals when their values change in code. For OptionButton nodes, this isn’t the case, so we need to use our setter functions to update the Viewport resolution and MSAA.

func reset_to_default_settings() -> void:
    _shadow_quality.value = ShadowFilter.PCF13
    _FXAA.pressed = false
    _resolution.select(0)
    set_resolution(0)
    _MSAA.select(0)
    set_msaa(0)

Making 3D Portals

This demo is about creating dimensional doors and other teleporters, as seen in the game Portal. At least, this demo covers the foundations to display another part of the world.

Note: Godot 3 lacks some features to create complete portals that would clip objects passing through them. You can learn more in this proposal: Godot proposals: add CameraMatrix to Variant.

Portals are views into another part of your game world. The player looks at some surface, and through it, they see another part of the game world.

Also, we typically want to connect two of such portals: one displays what is on the other side, and vice versa.

To achieve that, we need to render a different area as if the player was looking into it, relative to the portals’ positions and angles.

More precisely, you need to create a camera you position relative to the target part of the world you want to display (the pink line below).

Then, you need to offset it from the target, both in terms of position and rotation: the position and rotation of the player’s camera relative to the portal they are looking at.

And, of course, to render that other view of the world, we need a Viewport.

In this demo, our portals consist of a plane, the surface on which we display the other side of the world, a Viewport, and a Camera.

In code, we want to move that camera to the target portal to render what is in that other part of the game world.

We also need to calculate the player’s transform relative to this portal. To do so, we can export some node paths and get the corresponding nodes at the start of the game.

extends Spatial

## This is the path to the target portal we want to connect to this one.
export var target_path := NodePath()
## And this is the path to the player's camera/
export var player_camera_path := NodePath()

var _target: Spatial
var _player_camera: Spatial

## This portal's camera, which we place at the target portal's location.
onready var _camera: Camera = $Viewport/Camera


func _ready() -> void:
    _target = get_node(target_path)
    _player_camera = get_node(player_camera_path)

We then place the camera at the target location.

Below, I first calculate the position offset of the player’s camera, then the rotational offset. Both are relative to the portal the player is looking at.

func _physics_process(_delta: float) -> void:
    # We calculate the player's offset from the portal.
    var player_offset := to_local(_player_camera.global_transform.origin)
    # Then, we place the camera at the target portal and apply the player's offset.
    _camera.transform.origin = _target.global_transform.origin + player_offset
    
    # For the rotation, similarly, we calculate the rotational offset between the portal and the player.
    var local_rotation := global_transform.basis.inverse() * _player_camera.global_transform.basis
    # Then, we add that rotation to the target portal's current rotation.
    _camera.global_transform.basis = _target.transform.basis * local_rotation

If you’re unfamiliar with 3D transforms, you can learn more down below: What the origin and basis do.

Displaying and cropping the viewport’s texture

With the two exported NodePath properties, you can set up a portal by instantiating it in the game world and assigning nodes in the Inspector.

Once you create and assign the node paths for two portals, you can’t just display what the Viewport renders on your mesh: each portal’s Viewport renders the full camera’s view, but the mesh only takes a portion of the screen.

We want to map the portion of our ViewportTexture that corresponds to the surface of our portal in the view, which requires a shader. Luckily, in Godot, you only need a simple one.

shader_type spatial;
// Here, I don't want to cast shadows on the portal: I want a crisp view of the other side of the world. So I turn off any shading on this surface with the unshaded render mode.
render_mode unshaded;

// We assign a viewport texture targeting the portal viewport to this property.
uniform sampler2D portal_texture;


void fragment() {
    // Godot provides a property that directly maps the surface the mesh takes on the screen.
    // We use it to sample our texture, effectively cropping the rendered view to the portal's mesh.
    vec4 color = texture(portal_texture, SCREEN_UV);
    // And we output the pixels sampled from our portal viewport onto the screen.
    ALBEDO = color.rgb;
}

You want to assign that shader to a material on the portal’s surface.

You also need to ensure that every resource is local to the scene, meaning that every portal will get a unique ViewportTexture resource, a unique copy of the shader, and the material.

Under every resource in Godot, you can set that by expanding the folded Resource category.

What the origin and basis do

While short, the code to calculate the camera’s offset can seem like magic if you’re new to working with transforms. So here are some explanations regarding a transform’s origin and basis.

Godot exposes every node’s transforms and encourages you to work with them, as this leads to code that is often efficient to write and run.

A 3D transform is mainly composed of two elements: the origin and the basis. You can think of them respectively as the node’s position and its local 3D axes.

When dealing with global_transform, the origin is the node’s position relative to the world’s origin.

If you use the transform property instead, you are dealing with the position relative to the parent node.

The transform’s basis represents the node’s local axes, giving us information about its rotation and scale. It is a set of three vectors that define the node’s transformation axes.

You can see that in the editor when you toggle the transform gizmo between the world and local modes in the toolbar.

When we multiply two basis, we apply a node’s rotation onto another. If you inverse the basis, you remove that rotation from the basis you multiplied with.

Note that the order of operations matters here: you apply the basis on the left of the multiplication sign to the one on the right.

Your questions

How do I move a Viewport node on-screen?

If you want to position a minimap, you’ll want to move the node holding or showing the Viewport’s contents.

For Control nodes like TextureRect and ViewportContainer, change the rect_position and rect_size properties. For a Node2D like a Sprite, change the position property.

Note: A Sprite will automatically adjust its scale to fit the Viewport’s size property, so Sprite scale should be adjusted on the Viewport instead to avoid resampling issues.

How do I change the size of my Viewport?

When a Sprite has a ViewportTexture, it will automatically adjust its scale based on the Viewport size. Instead of changing the scale, you should change the size of the Viewport to avoid resampling issues.

If you want to change the resolution of a Viewport without changing its apparent size on-screen, the Viewport has to be a child of a ViewportContainer. When the ViewportContainer has stretch enabled, you can adjust the size of the Viewport without changing its apparent size on-screen.

Changing a ViewportContainer’s rect_size will stretch the look of the Viewport. You should change the margin properties of the ViewportContainer instead.

How do I make my screen fit to any window size?

If you run a 2D scene with some details, and expand the window, you’ll see beyond the usual playable space. While this can be partially solved by adding a Camera2D node, you can also lock the root Viewport’s aspect ratio to prevent it from showing outside the bounds of 2D.

This is not an issue in 3D since the Camera node adjusts what it can render automatically based on the screen size.

To lock the root Viewport’s aspect ratio, go to Project Settings > Display > Window > Stretch and set Aspect to keep. Then, choose a stretch mode:

  • 2D stretches the root Viewport without increasing resolution at all.
  • Viewport stretches the root Viewport but it scales UI elements up as needed.

You can read more about this topic with stretch mode and aspect in the Godot docs article for Multiple Resolutions.

How should I structure my scene with a Viewport?

Scene structure with a Viewport depends on the game. If you don’t need more than one view at a time, you don’t need a Viewport node. You can rely on Godot’s root viewport instead.

A Camera2D gives you more control over how your root viewport is panned and zoomed. You can read more about this node in the guide for Camera2D.

A Camera enables you to see the 3D world from the root viewport.

If you are using a secondary view, such as split screen, you can add any node as a child of the Viewport:

  • Control nodes will display inside their parent Viewport.
  • Node2D nodes are visible from any Camera2D, regardless of Viewport.
  • Spatial nodes are visible from any Camera, regardless of Viewport.

How do I hide nodes from a Viewport?

Assuming that you want a node to be visible in one Viewport, but hidden in another, there are two ways to control visibility: worlds and culling masks.

Viewports in 3D can adjust the cull_mask property of their Camera. This will show or hide any objects on that 3D render layer. Any visible 3D object in-game can be set to use a specific 3D render layer.

Render layers are a lot like the physics layers for collisions, except they only control visibility. You can name these 3D render layers in Project Settings > Layer Names > 3D Render.

Worlds are more involved. Two nodes in their own worlds will have separate rendering and collision. This is one way to control what is visible and collidable between Viewport.

  • Worlds in 3D can be set in the Inspector, by creating a new World resource, and enabling Own World.
  • World2D is only editable through code, by accessing Viewport.world2d.

How do I change the root viewport resolution at runtime?

In a 3D game, you generally want to let the player control the game’s resolution.

Lowering the resolution allows them to get better rendering performance.

At runtime, you can access the root viewport, which renders to the user’s display, with get_tree().get_root(). You can then change its size property to resize the viewport.

func _ready() -> void:
    # Set the root resolution to 960 by 540
    get_tree().get_root().size = Vector2(960, 540)

Note that this only affects the root viewport.

Suppose your game uses many viewports to render visual effects. In that case, you may want to iterate over them and change their resolution accordingly.

One way you could do that is with an Autoload (Godot’s equivalent of singletons).

You would have every Viewport node register itself there and let the singleton emit a signal to update their sizes.

How do I find out when a node has gone off-screen?

You may want to disable enemy functionality until they’re shown on-screen.

You can use VisibilityEnabler2D and VisibilityNotifier2D for this. Both have different effects when they’re a child of a Node2D

  • VisibilityEnabler2D freezes and pauses different parts of Nodes that are off-screen, without the need to use code.
  • VisibilityNotifier2D provides helper signals like screen_entered and screen_exited for coding custom functions.

Troubleshooting

This section covers general troubleshooting tips related to Viewport.

Why doesn’t my Viewport show anything?

Viewport can be complex to work with, and there’s several ways they won’t display as expected. Here’s some ways to check the Viewport, ViewportContainer, and code to figure out what’s gone wrong.

All Viewport:

  • Make sure each Viewport has a Camera2D or Camera as a child.
  • Enable the Current property on the Viewport’s camera.
  • Check that the Viewport size is large enough (example: x = 500 , y = 500) to let you see some details.
  • Click the hide icon, then click the show icon in the Scene dock to update the editor’s preview of any ViewportTexture resources and containers.
  • Set Clear Mode and Update Mode to Always.

Note: You can return the Update Mode and Clear Mode properties to default values to help optimize the viewport.

ViewportContainer:

  • Adjust the container’s margins in the 2D editor using the selection tool.
  • Enable the container’s Stretch property.
  • Set stretch_shrink to 1.

Code:

  • Review any code that calls get_texture.get_data() on a Viewport, or code that assigns images to a Texture.

ViewportTexture/Viewport is throwing a lot of errors

A lot of output errors can happen when setting up a ViewportTexture. All nodes that can carry a ViewportTexture ( Sprite, TextureRect, SpatialMaterial Albedo, etc.) are referred to as “render targets”. Here are the most common errors:

  • Cannot get path of node as it is not in a scene tree. - The node order of the scene tree matters. A Viewport has to be above the render target node. Change the node order so the render target is above the Viewport. A Viewport cannot be a child of the render target.
  • (Node not found...(relative to "").) - A node on the way to the Viewport was renamed, or moved. This error also happens if the Viewport is a child of the render target. Make sure to re-assign the ViewportTexture’s viewport_path.
  • Image width must be greater than 0. - The Viewport size isn’t set. Set its Size to the number of pixels it should cover.

Viewport is upside-down

If your Viewport is upside-down, enable V Flip in the Inspector. This is a necessary step for ViewportTexture resources, screenshots, and calling get_texture.get_data() on a Viewport. You can also call flip_y() on the image data returned from get_texture().get_data().

ViewportTexture: Path to node is invalid

ViewportTexture will sometimes emit this error: ViewportTexture: Path to node is invalid. This error occurs when the Viewport is lower in the scene tree than its render target (like a Sprite or a TextureRect). In practice this doesn’t stop the ViewportTexture from working, but the error can be fixed by:

  • Making the Viewport a sibling or a parent of the node with a ViewportTexture.
  • Placing the Viewport node above the node that has a ViewportTexture ( Sprite, TextureRect, or Mesh).
  • Reassigning the ViewportTexture’s viewport_path if you rename any node shown in the viewport_path.

No collision in multiplayer

If you have two Viewport nodes that should collide with each other (such as in split screen multiplayer) but they don’t collide, be sure to check:

  • All collision layers and masks are set appropriately (multiple players should use identical layers and masks).
  • own_world is false.
  • The World resource is empty.

If these don’t work, you can manually assign worlds in code to each Viewport. Use viewport_2.world = viewport_1.world for 3D and viewport_2.world2d = viewport_1.world2d for 2D.

Pro Tips

  • You can read more about how to scale the root viewport with Project Settings instead of code by reading the Godot docs article for Multiple Resolutions.

  • You can call set_attach_to_screen_rect(rect) on a Viewport to attach to the root Viewport directly. The Rect2 parameter determines the position and size of the new child Viewport. To move this attached viewport further, call the method again with a new Rect2.

  • You can access the root Viewport and make adjustments by using get_tree().get_root() on any Node.

  • You can get the specific Viewport that a node is using by calling get_viewport() from a node.

  • Sometimes you can get an error when calling get_texture().get_data() at the start of the game, or on every frame. This is because Godot’s VisualServer hasn’t fully loaded, and the Viewport’s data isn’t ready. To fix this, you can use yield(VisualServer, "frame_post_draw") before you call get_data() on a Viewport.

Clickable buttons in 3D

To get clickable buttons in 3D, you can check out the GUI in 3D demo on the Godot AssetLib. This system uses 3D raycasts from the mouse position to create a fake user input that reacts in 2D.

For AR and VR developers, the above demo has been adapted in Godot. The GUI in VR addon by aaronfranke on the Godot AssetLib has the system ported for VR controllers. You can also check out GUI in VR demo on the Godot AssetLib to try out the system.
